{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1774638921,"nonce":"BUMOHdevWe+CCF2fT5Td0NBZhmE=","title":"Modal serverless GPU integration for feedbax training","message":"Investigate and implement Modal (modal.com) as a serverless GPU provider for feedbax/rlrmp training experiments, replacing the current RunPod workflow.\n\n## Motivation\n\nCurrent RunPod workflow has significant friction:\n- Pod setup fragility: Python 3.12 + deps lost on spot preemption (see 216b368)\n- Idle GPU costs when experiments complete but pod stays running\n- Manual SSH/scp workflow for code push and result retrieval\n- Manual process management for concurrent experiments across GPUs\n- No reproducible environment (manual pip install on each pod)\n\nModal eliminates all of these: environment is code-defined, pay-per-second, `.map()` for parallelization, results returned programmatically.\n\n## Requirements\n\n1. **Generalized wrapper** — not specific to train_minimax.py or any particular architecture. Should work with any feedbax training script that takes CLI args and writes results to an output directory.\n2. **Image caching** — JAX + CUDA + feedbax + rlrmp pre-built, so cold starts are fast.\n3. **Result collection** — automatic download of results after runs complete.\n4. **`.map()` support** — distribute N conditions across M GPUs easily.\n5. **Local feedbax mounting** — support using local feedbax branch (for development) or pinned version.\n6. **Cost analysis** — compare Modal GPU options (A10G, A100, H100) vs current RunPod 2x4090 spot pricing.\n\n## Scope\n\n- Spec and prototype for the Modal wrapper\n- Cost/performance analysis\n- Migration plan from RunPod","files":null}]}